{"\ufeffDecoding Section 80G: How to Save Tax While Supporting a Cause\nGiving Smarter \u00b7 June 2026\nReading time: 7 minutes\n________________\n\n\nIt's that time of year again.\nYour HR sends the investment declaration reminder. Your CA asks for proof of savings. You start digging through folders for insurance receipts, home loan certificates, and PPF statements - and somewhere in the middle of all of it, you remember that you donated to a cause earlier this year.\nYou made the transfer. You felt good about it. And then life moved on.\nBut here's the part most people miss entirely: that donation you made - to the right organisation - could significantly reduce your taxable income this year.\nNot someday. This financial year. Right now, when it actually matters.\nIf you've heard of Section 80G but never quite understood what it means for you as a salaried professional, this blog is written for you. No jargon. No complicated tax language. Just a clear, honest explanation of how charitable giving and smart tax planning can work together - and how to make sure your donations count in both directions.\n________________\n\n\nWhat Is Section 80G, in Plain English?\nSection 80G is a provision in the Indian Income Tax Act that allows you to claim a deduction on your taxable income for donations made to eligible charitable organisations.\nIn simpler terms: when you donate to a registered, eligible organisation, the government lets you subtract a portion of that donation from your taxable income - which means you pay less tax.\nIt is the government's way of incentivising charitable giving. A signal that says: if you support causes that benefit society, we will reduce your tax burden in return.\nThe key word in all of this is eligible. Not every organisation qualifies. Not every donation counts. And the deduction you get - 50% or 100% - depends on which category the organisation falls under.\nThat distinction matters a lot. Let's break it down.\n________________\n\n\nThe Two Types of 80G Deductions: 50% vs 100%\nThis is the part that confuses most people, so let's be very clear about it.\nUnder Section 80G, donations are divided into two broad categories based on how much of your donation you can deduct from your taxable income:\n________________\n\n\n\ud83d\udfe2 100% Deduction - You Deduct the Full Amount You Donated\nIf an organisation is approved for 100% deduction, you can subtract the entire donation amount from your taxable income.\nExample: You earn \u20b912,00,000 per year. You donate \u20b920,000 to an organisation with 100% 80G approval. Your taxable income becomes \u20b911,80,000. You are taxed on the lower amount.\nOrganisations in this category typically include:\n* The Prime Minister's National Relief Fund (PMNRF)\n* The National Defence Fund\n* The National Foundation for Communal Harmony\n* Approved universities and educational institutions of national importance\n* Certain state government funds\n________________\n\n\n\ud83d\udfe1 50% Deduction - You Deduct Half of What You Donated\nIf an organisation is approved for 50% deduction, you can subtract only half the donated amount from your taxable income.\nExample: You donate \u20b920,000 to an organisation with 50% 80G approval. You can deduct \u20b910,000 from your taxable income.\nMost registered NGOs, charitable trusts, and giving platforms - including CauseKind - fall in this category. While 50% sounds like less, it is still a meaningful, real saving - and it is available to you on every eligible donation you make.\n________________\n\n\nThere Is One More Layer: With and Without Qualifying Limits\nHere is where many people get tripped up. Within both the 50% and 100% categories, there is a further distinction:\nWithout Qualifying Limit - You can claim the deduction on the full donated amount, regardless of your income.\nWith Qualifying Limit - Your deduction is capped at 10% of your Adjusted Gross Total Income (AGTI). Donations beyond that 10% threshold do not qualify for additional deduction.\nWhat is Adjusted Gross Total Income? It is your gross total income minus deductions under Sections 80C, 80D, and other applicable sections.\nMost salaried professionals donating reasonable amounts - say \u20b95,000 to \u20b950,000 per year - will rarely hit this 10% ceiling. But if you are making large charitable donations as part of your financial planning, this limit is worth knowing.\n________________\n\n\nLet's Make This Real With a Worked Example\nMeet Priya. She is a salaried professional in Mumbai earning \u20b915,00,000 per year.\nShe has already invested in 80C instruments (PPF, ELSS, LIC) totalling \u20b91,50,000 - the maximum deduction under 80C.\nIn February, she donates \u20b930,000 to a registered NGO that has 50% 80G approval with a qualifying limit.\nHere's how it works for her:\n\n\n\tAmount\n\tGross Total Income\n\t\u20b915,00,000\n\tLess: 80C Deductions\n\t\u20b91,50,000\n\tAdjusted Gross Total Income (AGTI)\n\t\u20b913,50,000\n\t10% of AGTI (qualifying limit)\n\t\u20b91,35,000\n\tDonation Made\n\t\u20b930,000\n\tDonation Eligible (within 10% limit)\n\t\u20b930,000 \u2705\n\t50% of Eligible Donation (deductible)\n\t\u20b915,000\n\tFinal Taxable Income\n\t\u20b913,35,000\n\tPriya's taxable income reduces by \u20b915,000. Depending on her tax slab, this saves her between \u20b93,000 and \u20b94,500 in actual tax paid.\nShe supported a cause she believes in. She received a tax benefit. And the NGO received the full \u20b930,000 - not a rupee less.\nThat is Section 80G working exactly as it is designed to.\n________________\n\n\nWhat You Actually Need to Claim This Deduction\nThis is the practical part. Claiming an 80G deduction is not complicated - but you need to have the right documentation. Here is what is required:\n\u2705 1. A Valid 80G Certificate from the Organisation\nThe organisation must have a current, valid 80G registration from the Income Tax Department. This is not permanent - organisations renew their registration, and the validity period matters. Always confirm the certificate is active at the time of your donation.\n\u2705 2. A Stamped, Official Donation Receipt\nYou need a receipt from the organisation that includes:\n* Your full name and address\n* PAN number of the donating organisation\n* Amount donated (in figures and words)\n* Date of donation\n* Mode of payment\n* Organisation's 80G registration number and validity\n\u2705 3. Payment via Traceable Mode\nThis is critical: Cash donations above \u20b92,000 are not eligible for 80G deduction. Your donation must be made via cheque, bank transfer, UPI, credit or debit card - any traceable electronic method.\nIf you donate \u20b95,000 in cash, you lose your right to claim it under 80G. Make the transfer digitally. Always.\n\u2705 4. Form 10BE - The New Requirement (From FY 2021-22 Onwards)\nFrom Financial Year 2021-22, organisations are required to file a statement of donations received with the Income Tax Department and issue a Form 10BE to donors. This form is now the primary document required to claim your 80G deduction when filing your ITR.\nDo not just rely on the donation receipt. Request Form 10BE from every organisation you donate to.\n________________\n\n\nWhen to Donate: Timing Your Giving for Maximum Tax Benefit\nThis is the section most financial advisors will not tell you, but it matters.\nThe Indian financial year runs from April 1 to March 31. Any donation you make within this window is eligible for that year's tax deduction - but only if it happens before March 31.\nIf you are thinking about a year-end donation and it is already late February or early March - act quickly. The last week of March is when many donors rush, and some organisations take time to process receipts and issue Form 10BEs.\nThe ideal time to plan your charitable giving is between October and February. This gives you:\n* Enough time to choose organisations carefully\n* Clarity on your income and existing deductions for the year\n* Time to receive proper documentation before your ITR filing\nThink of your charitable giving the same way you think of your PPF contribution or ELSS investment: plan it as part of your financial year, not as an afterthought.\n________________\n\n\nCommon Mistakes That Cost People Their Deduction\n\u274c Donating in Cash (Above \u20b92,000)\nAlready covered above - but worth repeating because it is the most common mistake. Cash donations above \u20b92,000 are simply not eligible. Full stop.\n\u274c Not Verifying the Organisation's Current 80G Status\nAn organisation may have had 80G approval in the past but may not have renewed it. Always ask for the current certificate. Check the validity dates.\n\u274c Forgetting to Collect Form 10BE\nA donation receipt is not enough for FY 2021-22 onwards. You need Form 10BE. Follow up with the organisation if you do not receive it before your ITR filing deadline.\n\u274c Donating to Ineligible Organisations\nDonations to individuals, political parties, foreign trusts, and religious institutions that do not have specific 80G approval are not deductible. Even if the cause is worthy, the deduction only applies to eligible organisations.\n\u274c Exceeding the 10% Qualifying Limit Without Realising It\nIf your total donations across all qualifying organisations exceed 10% of your AGTI, the excess does not get deducted. Spread across the year and plan your total giving with this ceiling in mind.\n________________\n\n\nHow CauseKind Handles 80G for You\nWhen you donate through CauseKind to an eligible campaign or cause, here is what you can expect:\nVerified 80G Status Every cause listed on CauseKind that offers 80G benefits is verified before being listed. You do not have to chase down certificates or wonder if the organisation qualifies.\nInstant Digital Receipts Every donation made through CauseKind - via UPI, bank transfer, or card - generates an immediate digital receipt with all required details. No chasing, no waiting.\nForm 10BE Support CauseKind works with partner organisations to ensure donors receive their Form 10BE in time for ITR filing. We make the paperwork as smooth as the giving.\n100% Traceable Payments All donations on CauseKind are processed through Razorpay - fully traceable, fully secure. Every transaction meets the digital payment requirement for 80G eligibility.\n________________\n\n\nThe Bigger Picture: Tax Saving Is the Bonus, Not the Point\nHere is something worth saying honestly.\n80G is a powerful tool for salaried professionals who want to be thoughtful about their finances. Using it wisely means your money does more - it supports a cause and reduces your tax outgo at the same time.\nBut it is worth remembering why this provision exists.\nThe government created Section 80G to encourage more Indians to support social causes - education, health, disaster relief, poverty alleviation. The tax saving is an incentive to give, not the reason to give.\nThe best version of charitable giving is when you find a cause that genuinely matters to you, give to it thoughtfully and consistently, and then - as a responsible salaried professional - also claim the legitimate tax benefit you are entitled to.\nGive because it matters. Claim because you should. Do both.\n________________\n\n\nYour 80G Checklist Before March 31\nUse this as your end-of-year giving checklist:\n* Identify causes you want to support this financial year\n* Verify that each organisation has a current, valid 80G registration\n* Make all donations via digital/traceable payment methods (UPI, bank transfer, card)\n* Collect official donation receipts from each organisation\n* Request Form 10BE from each organisation before April\n* Check that your total donations do not exceed 10% of your AGTI (for qualifying limit organisations)\n* Declare your donations when filing your ITR under Section 80G\n________________\n\n\nStart Here\nIf you are looking for verified, 80G-eligible causes to support this financial year, CauseKind is the place to start.\nEvery cause is vetted. Every donation is traceable. Every receipt is instant. And every rupee you give reaches the cause in full - not a paisa deducted in platform fees.\nGive with purpose. Save with clarity. Make this financial year count.\n________________\n\n\nBrowse 80G-Eligible Causes on CauseKind \u2192 Make a Verified, Tax-Saving Donation \u2192 Create Your Free CauseKind Account \u2192\n________________\n\n\nCauseKind is India's verified giving platform. Zero platform fees. 100% of your donation reaches the cause. Razorpay secured. Admin-verified listings.\nFor tax-related documentation or Form 10BE queries, contact us at support@causekind.org or +91 7719938619\n________________\n\n\nDisclaimer: This blog is intended for general informational purposes only and does not constitute professional tax or legal advice. Tax laws are subject to change. Please consult a qualified chartered accountant or tax advisor for guidance specific to your financial situation.\n________________\n\n\nTags: Section 80G tax deduction India, 80G donation tax saving, how to save tax by donating India, 80G 50% vs 100% deduction, tax benefit on charity India, salaried professional tax saving donation, 80G certificate India, Form 10BE donation, year end tax saving India, CauseKind 80G, donate and save tax India": null}